s a comprehensive survey of communications in the circumpolar region, focusing on the Canadian Arctic and sub-Arctic but also looking at the circumpolar North (Alaska, Siberia, Greenland, and the Nordic/Saami nations). Radio, television, magazines, newspapers, and web sites are all covered. As technologies and access improve, Aboriginal people are increasingly taking control of their own representation and consolidating their presence in northern media. Alia concludes that Canada will maintain its leadership in northern communications in the years ahead, given the topic's far-reaching importance and international context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndian mass mediazCanada, Northern. 0aIndigenous peoples and mass mediazCanada, Northern. 0aMass mediazCanada, Northern. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAlia, Valerie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiggins, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNores, Brenda G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485632440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774856324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774856324/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141940-4  University of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles